<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<speak version="1.1" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2001/10/synthesis">

<voice name="V2">
<prosody rate="95%" pitch="-2st">

Every demo you have ever seen of a language model <break time="400ms"/> lied to you.

<break time="600ms"/>

Not intentionally. <break time="300ms"/> But structurally. <break time="400ms"/> Every demo showed you a single interaction. <break time="300ms"/> A prompt goes in. <break time="200ms"/> A response comes out. <break time="300ms"/> Clean. <break time="200ms"/> Impressive. <break time="200ms"/> Complete.

<break time="600ms"/>

But that is not how work gets done.

<break time="500ms"/>

Real work is messy. <break time="200ms"/> It spans multiple steps. <break time="200ms"/> It requires looking things up and making decisions. <break time="200ms"/> It requires handling errors and circling back.

<break time="400ms"/>

Real work is a <emphasis level="moderate">loop</emphasis>, not a line.

<break time="600ms"/>

That loop is exactly what separates a language model from an agent.

<break time="800ms"/>

In this module, we go inside the loop. <break time="300ms"/> We break down the components. <break time="300ms"/> We show you what it means to build AI that works.

<break time="1200ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Defining the Agent.

<break time="500ms"/>

Let us define the term clearly.

<break time="500ms"/>

Definition: An agent is a system that uses a language model as its reasoning core, wrapped in a control loop for planning, acting, observing, and adapting.

<break time="500ms"/>

The key word is loop.

<break time="500ms"/>

In single-call inference, you make one request and get one response. <break time="300ms"/> The model has no awareness of what came before. <break time="300ms"/> Every interaction is isolated.

<break time="500ms"/>

Failure mode: no continuity between steps.

<break time="500ms"/>

In agentic systems, the model operates inside a cycle. <break time="300ms"/> It receives a goal. <break time="200ms"/> It plans steps. <break time="200ms"/> It executes an action. <break time="200ms"/> It observes the result. <break time="300ms"/> Then it decides what to do next.

<break time="400ms"/>

This cycle repeats until the goal is complete or the system escalates.

<break time="600ms"/>

Definition: The <emphasis level="moderate">agent loop</emphasis> is the foundational pattern behind every agentic system.

<break time="500ms"/>

But the loop alone is not enough. <break time="300ms"/> To be useful, agents need components.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: The Six Core Components.

<break time="500ms"/>

There are six core components in a production agentic architecture.

<break time="600ms"/>

Planning. <break time="300ms"/> The agent breaks a complex goal into smaller subtasks. <break time="200ms"/> It sequences them logically. <break time="200ms"/> It adjusts when things go wrong.

<break time="400ms"/>

For engineers: planning can be explicit via a planner module or implicit via model reasoning.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: hybrid approaches work best in production.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">Tool use</emphasis>. <break time="300ms"/> An agent without tools is just a chatbot with a loop. <break time="300ms"/> Tools let agents interact with the world beyond text.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: Tools are interfaces including APIs, code interpreters, search engines, and enterprise connectors.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: actionability. <break time="300ms"/> Tools bridge reasoning and reality.

<break time="600ms"/>

Memory. <break time="300ms"/> Agents need to remember. <break time="300ms"/> Short-term memory holds current task context. <break time="300ms"/> Long-term memory persists across sessions.

<break time="400ms"/>

For engineers: working memory is per-task, long-term memory is persistent storage.

<break time="400ms"/>

Failure mode: without memory, agents forget what they just did.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">Retrieval and grounding</emphasis>. <break time="300ms"/> Retrieval accesses external knowledge via vector databases or search. <break time="300ms"/> Grounding anchors responses in retrieved facts.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: Grounding means the model's output is tied to specific retrieved data, not just parametric knowledge.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: grounding reduces hallucination.

<break time="600ms"/>

Safety and policy. <break time="300ms"/> Production agents operate within guardrails. <break time="300ms"/> Content filters block harmful outputs. <break time="200ms"/> Policy engines enforce business rules.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: compliance. <break time="300ms"/> Safety is a core architectural layer.

<break time="400ms"/>

For product and technical leaders: policy enforcement involves legal, compliance, and risk teams.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">Human-in-the-loop</emphasis>. <break time="300ms"/> Not every decision should be automated. <break time="300ms"/> Agents need escalation mechanisms.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: HITL is the capacity to pause, present state, and request human input.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: critical for high-stakes domains and low-confidence cases.

<break time="600ms"/>

These six components form the anatomy of an agent. <break time="300ms"/> If any one is missing, the system is incomplete.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Real-World Workflow Examples.

<break time="500ms"/>

Let us connect this to how real work gets done.

<break time="500ms"/>

Consider a support automation workflow. <break time="300ms"/> A customer submits a ticket. <break time="300ms"/> The agent retrieves customer history from a CRM. <break time="200ms"/> It identifies relevant knowledge base articles. <break time="200ms"/> It formulates a response. <break time="200ms"/> It routes for escalation if needed.

<break time="500ms"/>

That is not one call. <break time="300ms"/> That is a loop with tool invocations, memory access, and human handoff.

<break time="600ms"/>

Or consider a research workflow. <break time="300ms"/> An analyst needs a market summary. <break time="300ms"/> The agent queries multiple data sources. <break time="200ms"/> It synthesizes findings. <break time="200ms"/> It checks for consistency. <break time="200ms"/> It generates a report.

<break time="500ms"/>

For product and technical leaders: these workflows replace manual processes, not just chat interfaces.

<break time="600ms"/>

Enterprises adopt agentic systems because their workloads are multi-step processes. <break time="300ms"/> They require coordination, verification, and adaptation.

<break time="500ms"/>

Enterprise driver: <emphasis level="moderate">workflow automation</emphasis>. <break time="300ms"/> The shift from demos to workloads is the shift from single calls to loops.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Certification Alignment.

<break time="500ms"/>

This module establishes vocabulary and concepts for the certification exam.

<break time="500ms"/>

The certification expects you to understand what distinguishes an agent from a single model call. <break time="300ms"/> The answer is the loop.

<break time="500ms"/>

This concept is covered in the certification under agent fundamentals and component recognition.

<break time="500ms"/>

Expect questions asking you to identify component responsibilities. <break time="300ms"/> Expect questions asking what is missing when a system fails.

<break time="500ms"/>

Key terms: agent loop, tool use, <emphasis level="moderate">grounding</emphasis>, retrieval, working memory, long-term memory, guardrails, HITL. <break time="300ms"/> Precise understanding matters.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="98%">

Section: Key Takeaways.

<break time="600ms"/>

An agent wraps a language model in a control loop. <break time="300ms"/> That loop enables planning, action, observation, and adaptation.

<break time="500ms"/>

The agent loop has six components. <break time="200ms"/> Planning. <break time="150ms"/> Tools. <break time="150ms"/> Memory. <break time="150ms"/> Retrieval. <break time="150ms"/> Safety. <break time="150ms"/> Human-in-the-loop.

<break time="500ms"/>

Demos show single calls. <break time="300ms"/> Real workloads require loops.

<break time="500ms"/>

Enterprises adopt agents because their problems are multi-step and require verification. <break time="300ms"/> Agents are the architecture that fits.

<break time="500ms"/>

The loop is the foundation. <break time="300ms"/> Everything else builds on it.

<break time="1000ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

</speak>
